The University of Uyo Women Association (UWA), yesterday, took to the streets of Uyo, Akwa-Ibom State capital to protest against rape and sexual violence in the state. Addressing the women, president of the association, Mrs. Rosalyn Enefiok Essien, said the once admirable moral fabric of the African traditional society has, in recent time, been blighted by the depressing act of rape predominantly carried out by the male gender. She explained that the association, in fulfillment of its social mandate, came out to protest, to say no to rape and other Gender Based Violence (SGBV). “We are here to lend our voices to the trending local, national and global advocacy against rape, in the wake of increasing Sexual and Gender Based Violence (SGBV) since the beginning of the lockdown” “All categories of females from babies to toddlers, teenagers to young ladies, middle aged women to grannies, have suffered varying act of male sexual violence; while  perpetrators have included family members, neighbours, landlords, teachers, the police, and other security forces. “No single individual, organisation, foundation or government can stop the epidemic, except by responding to the responsibility of tackling the problem collectively,’’ she stated. She said sexual violence affects all lives and the protest was a chance to say No to Rape, Sexual Violence, Child Sexual Abuse, Sex Trafficking, and other harmful practices in our communities. This disgusting reality she noted, has provided necessary and sufficient attractions for the University of Uyo Women Association to ventilate its reaction in the form of a social protest. “We are here today to extend the frontier of the existing social movement against rape using a speech-act process from the de-politicised through the politicised to the scrutinised.